title: For Sale/Trade:  Charter Arms AR-7 Explorer
postcontent:
This is the Charter Arms AR-7. Henry Repeating Arms is the current manufacturer.
First designed by Armalite in 1959, the venerable AR-7 has been the choice of U.S. Air Force pilots who need a small-caliber rifle they can count on for survival should they have to punch out over a remote area. Over the years, the AR-7's reputation for portability, ease of operation and reliability has carried over to the civilian world as well.
Today, it's a favorite of bush pilots, backpackers and backcountry adventurers who, like their Air Force counterparts, need a rifle that's easy to carry but has the accuracy to reliably take down small game.
This innovative, semi-automatic rifle is lightweight (just 2.5 lbs) and highly portable. At just 16 ½" long (when all the components are stowed), it fits easily into the cargo area of a plane or boat or in a backpack. And because it's chambered in .22LR you can carry a large quantity of ammunition, without adding much weight to your gear.
When disassembled, the pieces fit inside the impact-resistant, water-resistant stock. Assembly is as easy as attaching the receiver to the stock, inserting the barrel and screwing on the barrel nut. In just a few seconds, without the need for any tools, the AR-7 is ready for action.
The AR-7 has a sturdy steel barrel covered in aluminum and then coated with Teflon for complete protection against corrosion. Plus, it's engineered for perfect balance and the ability to maintain its tack-driving accuracy, even after thousands of rounds.
Like the barrel, the receiver is also coated with a layer of waterproof Teflon for superior weatherproofing, waterproof protection, even in harsh salt water environments.
It is equipped with an adjustable rear peep sight and a blade front sight.

title: For Sale:  Steyr M95 Carbine 8x56R - Complete Package + Free Stuff!
location: Lexington, NC, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent:
Up for sale is an all-numbers-matching Steyr M95 carbine in excellent condition, rated at 90% by blue book standards. This package is for anyone who has ever wanted to buy one of these rifles in range-ready condition to see what they are all about. When this package arrives, you will be fully prepared to spend hours at the range breaking in this little gem!

This rifle features a straight-pull Steyr-Mannlicher bolt design and is fed by a 5-round enbloc magazine in a style similar to the M1 Garand, where the clip is metal and is ejected from the bottom of the magazine housing when the last round is chambered. 

All items included in this package have been opened and inspected; the gun has a smooth mirror-like bore with strong lands/grooves, no surface rust or pitting of any kind, and the stock bears many dings and scuffs evident in old military surplus rifles, but it still has rich color and a good finish.

All enbloc magazines have been inspected and only one or two of them have very minimal surface rust that can be dealt with using a little elbow grease in about 15 minutes. *9* of these clips are included in this package, and if you look around the net, these are worth $10 each, so if you feel like 9 is too many, you are free to sell some of them to fellow M95 shooters who are in need of some that are in nearly pristine order!

Included for free with this rifle (that's right, I said FREE) is a rubber recoil pad that is very snug around the butt of the gun, along with a sling that was designed for use with the M95 carbine, and finally a hard gun case to carry around the newest addition to your collection! (A $50 value for all included!)

title: For Sale:  Anschutz Competition Target Rifle  .22 LR
postcontent: This is a very cool Anschutz competition target rifle in .22 LR caliber.  It has the model 2007 / 2013 square bottomed benchrest action, single shot,  with 19.5 inch bull barrel, mated to a laminated wood stock, fully adjustable for cheek weld height and length of pull.   This stock is no longer commercially available anymore, and can only be found on the secondary market these days, if anywhere, and was 950 dollars new (just for the stock alone...) back in the day.  I believe the trigger is their two stage model 5018, set at a only few ounces of pull, so very light and fast lock time.  The stock has the removable extension weight system applied to the front forearm, and there is a pin on the barrel for a bloop tube which can be acquired separately.   I am the original owner and have the original Anschutz factory test targets that came with the barreled action, and it lived up to its billing and easily used to put 10 rounds of ELEY Tenex into a rough circle at 50 yards in calm conditions.  While over 10 years old, like many of my "toys," it is actually very lightly used and has only a few hundred rounds through it, at most, which is absolutely nothing for a 22 LR barrel.  The reason why this and so much of my stuff is so lightly used and in such great condition, is bc back in the day, when I was first getting into target shooting but didn't exactly know what type of shooting I wanted to do, I bought a lot of different stuff in different calibers.....and so my shooting time was spread out over many different items, as I just jumped from toy to toy.  I had 223's and 308's and 22-250's etc etc etc    In some sense, I was almost spending more time shopping and buying, than shooting..... So no single thing was ever heavily used.  And then I took a break from shooting while into other things, and didn't shoot for almost 6 1/2 years.  So everything just sort of sat in a "time capsule," well cared for, but unused. Anyway, the scope on this rifle can also come along with the rig, or be sold separately. It's a Leupold 6.5 x 20 x 40 target scope.  Weight of rifle with scope is about 13 pounds.  I cant find any criticism of the rig, it's a great gun.  Only thing I might do if I were to keep shooting it instead of selling it, is perhaps glass bed the action (right now it's just a screwed down action torqued to Anschutz specs).  As recently as about 2008 when I last saw they were still selling these model 2007 / 2013 benchrest actions (they might be discontinued now, I'm not sure, I can't find them on the internet now anymore), they were going for over 2,000 just for the barreled action alone, not including stock or any accessories, for which I do specifically recall paying over 950 just for the stock.  So I'm asking roughly half of what I had into the gun, which I think is very reasonable given it was hardly used at all.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Sept 14th! Shoot To Win A Military Surplus Rifle AND A 'Bring Your Own' Shoot Off'
postcontent:
Saturday September 14th (moved to the 2nd week of Sept. to avoid labor day weekend at the Lake)

1 EVENT 2 SHOOT OFF COMPETITIONS!! WIN A 1954.11 (made November of 1954) TYPE 53 Mosin Nagant Carbine and BRING YOUR PERSONAL RIFLE & OUT SHOOT EVERYONE ELSE FOR 50% OF THE ENTRY FEE!

Details of both are below:

SHOOT #5
Saturday September 14th join us for the 5th Linn Creek Military Surplus Shoot Off. Starts at 12 noon!

You will have a chance to win a 1954.11 Type 53 Mosin Nagant Carbine (7.62x54r). I have personally cleaned and serviced this rifle from the ground up. I can say with 100% certainty, this is a very nice shooter and will be a welcome addition to any collection.

The shoot off general rules/info:

EAR PROTECTION IS MANDATORY! NO EXCEPTIONS!

The cost is $20 for each entry ticket or 3 for $50. 

Enter as many times as you like or can afford...lol. Cash payment at the time of the shoot. I am also open to trades of guns, ammo or any interesting military surplus/survival gear.

"What do we shoot for the event?" 
Everyone shoots the same rifle.... The prize rifle you are trying to win.

"How does it work?"

It's very simple. after everyone has paid & gotten their tickets, shooting order will be a random draw.

You shoot 5 rounds at 100 yards, open sights with ammo that I provide. Military surplus ammo straight from the spam can. In this case 188 gr Bulgarian surplus ammo.

No practice shots with the prize rifle. You go in cold just like everyone else. 

You can sit at the bench (no shooting rests, sleds, props or whatever, just the rifle & your arms), sitting, prone or standing as you so choose. This is an informal shoot, so please, no hardcore rule umpires, we want to keep it casual & easy going. In event of a tie there will be a 1 shot 'shoot off'. In the event of any disagreements/disputes, my judgement is final. 

We will spot and show you where your rounds are landing. 

Best points score takes the rifle home. It's that simple. Shoot 5 rounds, get the high score & take the rifle home with you. 

Obviously, you must be present to win. 
*******************************************************************
***************BRING YOUR OWN RIFLE & SHOOT TO WIN**************
*******************************************************************

It's pretty simple. 

$5 gets you in. Bring 5 rounds of your own ammo, shoot it out of your gun at 200 yards. High score wins.

Any caliber rifle, scoped or not at your preference. At the bench, off hand, sitting or prone. Your choice, no rests or bi pods. 

As reported to me by a few friends that are attending, there are .22's, .243, 30/30 and 7.62x54r, 7.5swiss 6.5 carcano, 7 & 8MM Mausers and so much more.

Do you have a nail driver? Bring it, show off your chops & take a few bucks home along with the bragging rights!

Highest score with 5 rounds will win you 1/2 (50%) of the entry fees to the 'bring your own' shoot. 

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Feel free to bring a few weapons/accessories to trade and or show off. After the shoot off it will be open range time for anyone wanting to shoot. There is a 300 yd range, pistol and shotgun pits as well. 

The range is in Linn Creek on A Rd. Located between Camdenton and Osage Beach. After you are on A rd. you will travel about 4 1/2 miles to Garrison. It will be a right turn, the only way you can go. Follow the gravel rd to the bottom of the hill & just across the low water bridge you will see Centerpoint gun club on the right. That is where we will be meeting for the shoot.

Don't worry about the drive. If you are in MO, it's not too far. We have folk coming in from every corner of the state. Joplin, KC, St Louis, St. Joseph and farther out. hop in the car and make the drive. I assure you it's worth the windshield time!

My phone number is REDACTED. If you have questions, want to discuss trade goods for tickets or need directions please feel free to call me between 10 am and midnight, 7 days a week.

My direct email is REDACTED

Linn Creek Milsurp Shoot Off group page on Facebook. Please feel free to join our FB group for updates, pics and more. 
https://www.facebook.com/groups/REDACTED77918/

There is no age limit, if you can handle & fire the weapon safely, your welcome to come and play with us. 

This is a primitive site. You will need to bring lawn chairs/something to sit on. Water isn't a bad idea. I always have some there for everyone, but extra never hurts. I hope to see you there!

This is a family event & is a LOT of fun with like minded folk. Come on down, meet new friends and enjoy a beautiful summer day in the Ozarks.

Once again, innovation is the “watch” word for 5.11 Tactical Series. When we set out to design a Titanium Watch we wanted one that would truly serve the needs of law enforcement. The SureShot® calculator gives you point of impact shooting solutions out to 1000 meters. Input your known ballistic data (bore height, ballistic coefficient, muzzle velocity and zero range), then add your environmental data (range, temperature, altitude, inclination) and the SureShot® calculator will give you a shooting solution in MILS, TMOA or SMOA. Value

title: For Sale/Trade:  NEW Beretta 92M9 9mm LNIB with (2) 15-round Mags
postcontent:
This Beretta is in like new condition. This is a new production model. It was purchased new approximately two months ago. It comes in the original box with two 15-round magazines in like new condition. MSRP is $775 on berettausa.com, but you can probably find one new for $675-$700 at most gun shops. The difference between this M9 and a brand new one is the price tag and the sales tax. That's it. Price is firm at $550. Would prefer a trade.

The M9 is a short recoil, semi-automatic, single-action / double-action pistol which uses a 15-round staggered box magazine with a reversible magazine release button that can be positioned for either right- or left-handed shooters. The M9 is used with the Bianchi M12 Holster, though other holsters are often used. The specific modifications made from the 
Beretta 92 includes:
- Design of all the parts to make them 100% interchangeable to simplify maintenance for large government organizations.
- Modified the front of the trigger guard so that one could use finger support for easier aiming.
- Recurved the forward base of the grip to aid aiming.
- Hard chromed the barrel bore to protect it from corrosion and to reduce wear.
- New surface coating on the slide called Bruniton, which allegedly provides better corrosion resistance than the previous plain blued finish.
- Enlarged hammer pin that fits into a groove on the underside of the slide. The main purpose is to stop the slide from flying off the frame to the rear if it cracks. This was in response to reported defective slides during U.S. Military testing.

The M9 was updated to the M9A1 in 2006. It added—among other things—a Picatinny rail for the attachment of lights, lasers, and other accessories to the weapon. The M9A1 has more aggressive front and backstrap checkering and a beveled magazine well for easier reloading of the weapon. M9A1 pistols are sold with physical vapor deposition (PVD) coated magazines developed to better withstand the conditions in the sandy environments in Iraq and Afghanistan.[8]

The M9 features multiple internal safeties, including a firing pin block that prevents the firing pin from moving without the trigger being pulled, and a firing pin striker that rotates when the safety lever is engaged preventing the firing pin from being hit even if the hammer falls. The M9 also has an ambidextrous external safety lever allowing both left and right handed people to comfortably engage the safety mechanism.
